{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01FZaj9V7Su862f6FoDg7ypa","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Oracle passes. Here's a summary of what was done and why:\n\n**Root cause:** The Elasticsearch cluster was inherited from an earlier stage (stage_02) with no file realm configured. The cluster used only the native realm, so neither `ops-user` nor `report-user` (both file-realm users) could authenticate.\n\n**Fix applied (3 changes, no operators/CRDs):**\n\n1. **Merged `user-provided-file-realm` into `es-file-realm-aggregate`** — patched the aggregate secret to contain both `ops-user` and `report-user` entries (users + users_roles).\n\n2. **Updated the `es-config` ConfigMap** — added `xpack.security.authc.realms.file.file1.order: 0` and `xpack.security.authc.realms.native.native1.order: 1` to enable the file realm alongside the existing native realm.\n\n3. **Updated the `elasticsearch` StatefulSet** — added the `es-file-realm-aggregate` secret as a volume and mounted it as `users`, `users_roles`, and `roles.yml` at `/usr/share/elasticsearch/config/`. This triggered a rolling restart (all 3 pods cycled one at a time, cluster stayed green throughout).\n\nAfter restart: `report-user` authenticates via the file realm, `ops-user` does too, the `elastic` native user still works, and the seeded `app-data` index is readable by `report-user`."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":207,"cache_read_input_tokens":61696,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":207},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"7e179615-5b60-4d30-9419-ea104fd0d74c","uuid":"18e110c1-9270-4e41-90e4-bed56074c044","request_id":"req_011CcP55Xbt2duGiFv73UWhU"}
